	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64145689"><p>That sounds like a really stupid use case.</p><p>I can think of a lot more practical ones. One of the hardest things about putting voice actors in games is that the dialogue has to be planned well in advance, and any part of the game designed to be dynamic to add immersion ends up in a loop, and you keep hearing the same shit over and over again. Take the side conversations in elder scrolls for example.</p><p>Or better yet, mods. Modders, who create stuff for free obviously can't afford to hire vice actors. The mods are usually pretty good, but it's a bit jarring having much of it text only in a game heavy on voice acting.</p><p>Paying the actor for every hour of voices generated is an incredibly dumb idea and makes this basically useless. Even your dumb "say the player's name" idea wouldn't work with that, because literally every time you get a new name, somebody has to get paid. Given the virtually limitless character names somebody might pick, that obviously won't scale. Otherwise you're taking about a limited number of selectable names, in which case, why fuckin bother?</p></div>
	</div>

